nodes.info:
This can range from a unit to a single person, an entire tank to a single bolt, and a mountain to a pile of dirt. Objects may not only be physical objects but also intangible or abstract objects such as rendezvous points, phase lines, and boundaries.
Class Object is non-abstract to support tracking situations where, initially, the object being tracked cannot be definitively classified.

nodes.name: Air defence radar site

nodes.name: Transport facility

nodes.name: Airborne early warning ground facility

nodes.name: Aircraft

nodes.name: Vehicle
nodes.label: Vehicle
nodes.description: A conveyance for transporting persons or things.

nodes.name: Airfield
nodes.label: Airfield
nodes.description: An area prepared for the accommodation (including buildings and installations) or equipment of landing and take-off of aircraft.

nodes.name: Airport or airbase
nodes.label: Airport or airbase
nodes.description: An air transport facility used for the landing and take-off of aircraft, including its buildings and installations.

nodes.name: Airspace control feature
nodes.source: MIM 5.3 (air control feature; orbit control feature; air route)
nodes.label: Airspace control feature
nodes.description: Control feature used to organise, enable, constrain, or deconflict air operations via routes, holds/orbits, and airspace volumes.
nodes.info: Decision & alignment: Consolidates MIM 'air control feature', 'orbit control feature', and 'air route' into a single operational class focused on air C2 and deconfliction. Rationale: in exercises these are governed together (ACO/ACA), share geometry types (line/area/volume) and attributes (altitude bands, timing, controlling authority). Specific doctrinal terms (e.g., CAP orbit) should be captured as instance categories rather than separate classes.

nodes.name: Control feature
nodes.label: Control feature
nodes.description: A non-tangible Feature of military interest that is administratively specified, may be represented by a geometric figure, and is associated with the conduct of military operations.
nodes.info: A ControlFeature is an abstract object created or assigned by military authorities for the purposes of planning and coordination, especially in operational areas. It is a non-permanent point (e.g., start point for a road move, or a reserved demolition), line (e.g., a Main supply route or No fire line), area (e.g., a Slow-go area), or volume (e.g., an air corridor) that may be overlaid on a map. A ControlFeature would normally be drawn on a map overlay, traced, or superimposed onto digitised map data and assigned a descriptive title, symbol, or name (e.g., Line of departure, Corps boundary).

nodes.name: Anchorage
nodes.label: Anchorage
nodes.description: A place where a vessel may anchor, usually designated in charts, offering suitable holding ground and shelter.

nodes.name: Maritime transport facility
nodes.label: Maritime transport facility
nodes.description: A facility designed to aid or enable transport of goods or passengers by sea or inland waterways.

nodes.name: Apron
nodes.label: Apron
nodes.description: A defined area on a land aerodrome intended to accommodate aircraft for the purposes of loading or unloading passengers, mail or cargo, fuelling, parking or maintenance.

nodes.name: Armoured personnel carrier
nodes.label: Armoured personnel carrier
nodes.description: A lightly armoured, highly mobile vehicle used primarily for transporting personnel and their individual equipment during tactical operations.

nodes.name: Army military base or facility
nodes.label: Army military base or facility
nodes.description: Army installation used for accommodation, training, logistics, or command.

nodes.name: Artillery locating site
nodes.label: Artillery locating site
nodes.description: Facility where artillery-locating sensors or systems are deployed.

nodes.name: Assault gun
nodes.label: Assault gun
nodes.description: A cannon, with a relatively long barrel, operating with a relatively low angle of fire, and having a high muzzle velocity.

nodes.name: Cannon
nodes.label: Cannon
nodes.description: A weapon for firing projectiles, having a heavy metal tube installed on a carriage or mounting.

nodes.name: Authorised Commander
nodes.label: Authorised commander
nodes.description: Base Commander

nodes.name: CyberC2
nodes.label: Cyber C2
nodes.description: Ability to plan, direct, coordinate, and monitor cyber operations (DODIN ops, DCO, OCO), ensuring commanders intent, battlespace management, and ROE compliance across all echelons.

nodes.name: CyberSupportCoordination
nodes.label: Cyber support coordination
nodes.description: Ability to orchestrate and synchronize cyber-related support across units and stakeholders (tasking, deconfliction, liaison with CSIRTs/ISPs/coalition), integrating cyber into joint planning and sustainment.

nodes.name: Bank
nodes.label: Bank
nodes.description: An establishment where money is stored for saving or commercial purposes.

nodes.name: Commercial facility
nodes.label: Commercial facility
nodes.description: A facility designed to enable or support commercial business processes.

nodes.name: Barracks
nodes.label: Barracks
nodes.description: Military accommodation facility for personnel and unit support.

nodes.name: Basin
nodes.label: Basin

nodes.name: Berth
nodes.label: Berth

nodes.name: Bivouac
nodes.label: Bivouac

nodes.name: Disrupt

nodes.label: Disrupt

nodes.name: Built up area
nodes.label: Built up area

nodes.name: City
nodes.label: City
nodes.description: Facility representing a built-up area at city scale, typically with high population density and diverse administrative and economic functions.

nodes.name: Hamlet
nodes.label: Hamlet
nodes.description: Facility representing a very small built-up area or settlement, usually a few dwellings with minimal services.

nodes.name: Town
nodes.label: Town
nodes.description: Facility representing a medium-sized built-up area, larger than a village and smaller than a city, with local services and governance.

nodes.name: Urban Area
nodes.label: Urban Area
nodes.description: Facility representing a contiguous built environment comprising cities, towns, and suburbs with predominantly non-rural land use.

nodes.name: Village
nodes.label: Village
nodes.description: Facility representing a small built-up area or settlement, typically rural, with limited services.

nodes.name: C2 boundary feature
nodes.label: C2 boundary feature
nodes.description: Control feature that delineates responsibilities, sectors, or areas of operation for command and control.
nodes.info: Decision & alignment: Groups MIM 'c2 control feature' and 'organisation boundary' as a single class because both express C2 delimitations (AOs, sectors, limits of responsibility). Rationale: operational semantics are identical (named boundary/area with authority, timeframe); the exact doctrinal label (e.g., corps boundary, AO, FLOT/FEBA) is modelled as an instance category.

nodes.name: CBRN control feature
nodes.label: CBRN control feature
nodes.description: Control feature defining CBRN-related areas, routes, or volumes for protection, decontamination, or hazard management.
nodes.info: Decision & alignment: Direct consolidation of MIM 'cbrn control feature'. Rationale: CBRN corridors, hazard areas, and decontamination zones share the same control semantics; the specific C/B/R/N modality and posture are instance attributes.

nodes.name: CyberDefensive

nodes.name: Force Protection

nodes.name: CyberForceProtection
nodes.label: Cyber force protection

nodes.name: Engineering
nodes.label: Engineering capability
nodes.description:
A Capability, required for planning, of those Organisations and Persons that are deemed as having the ability to perform construction or destruction activities. This includes performing mobility and counter-mobility tasks. 

Remarks:

EngineeringCapability provides additional information concerning the conditions for which the engineering capability is defined, that is, the type of facility which is being constructed or destroyed (or in the case of obstacles, breached) as well as the dimensions of that facility. Engineering capabilities can be described for different echelon levels. For instance, a bridge-building platoon may be capable of either constructing two bridges, each 20 metres long, or a single bridge that is 40 metres long. A company that is made up of three platoons may therefore be capable of building a single bridge that is 120 metres long. The first capability can be described at platoon level, the second at company level.

nodes.name: Manoeuvre
nodes.label: Manoeuvre
nodes.description: Positions and moves forces to gain positional advantage and create favorable conditions for success.

nodes.name: Fire
nodes.label: Fire capability
nodes.description:
A Capability, required for planning, of those Facilities, Equipment, Organisations and Persons that are deemed as having the ability to discharge or launch a projectile or missile.

FireCapability provides additional information about the type of projectile, which is being discharged or launched.

nodes.name: Handling
nodes.label: Handling capability

nodes.name: Maintenance

nodes.name: Mobility

nodes.description:
A Capability, required for planning, of those Facilities, Materiel, Organisations and Persons that are deemed as having the nominal ability to move in space, air, on water, under water, or over a specific type of terrain. 

Remarks:

MobilityCapability specifies additional information about the kind of mobility and, in certain cases, the conditions for which the manoeuvre capability is defined, in particular, the type of terrain that is being traversed.

nodes.name: Operational
nodes.label: Operational capability
nodes.description:
A Capability, required for planning, of those Objects that are deemed as having the ability, the training and the equipment to perform an operation.

Remarks:

OperationalCapability permits operational roles to be assigned to units or types of units, or in addition to the roles that are inherent in the typing of units.

nodes.name: Unit
nodes.label: Unit
nodes.description: A MilitaryOrganisation whose structure is prescribed by competent authority.
nodes.info:
The structure is prescribed, e.g., in the form of a table of organisation and equipment; specifically, part of an organisation. A formation is specified as a Unit.
One aim of Unit is to permit unique specification of tables of organisation and equipment (referred to in this model as Establishment) for any unit of interest within the scope of the model. A second aim is to provide information that is necessary for generating unit symbology for situation displays.

Each nation has a different way of classifying its own units. The model supports the representation of as many types of Units as possible (within the constraints of common sense). It should be recognised that the manner of classifying units may not correspond to national classification policy. However, national implementations of external displays for operational users can (and should) be built to support the national doctrine and naming conventions. The internal classification within a C2 application (based on the model) can be entirely invisible to the user of that application.

[Techopedia] Data Exfiltration is an abstract class intended as an organizational construct.
CyberEvent.Target identifies the data being exfiltrated. CyberEvent.ActorID identifies the actor performing the exfiltration.
